    ATONEMENT HEALING Scriptural or Unscriptural?
    Atonement healing is a popular message preached in the Pentecostal and Neo-Pentecostal churches.  It is based on the premise that through Christ’s suffering and death the effects of the Adamic curse were nullified.  It maintains that what satan stole and destroyed, Jesus completely restored.
    Ever since the late 19 th century and the beginning of the twentieth century, there has been a revival of the supernatural gifts of the Spirit.  With this came a new interest in Divine healing.  Even today its popularity is still on the increase in many evangelical churches. People seem to be searching for a more real experience in their Christian walk.  They are yearning for answers to life’s problems and sorrows.  They are leaving the mainline churches because the preaching of a watered-down gospel has left them empty and, consequently, they are in search of a dynamic, personal gospel message.  They want to believe that “God is still on the throne, and prayer changes things”.
    This paper will attempt to address the topic of healing from a sound, biblical approach.  At the outset, we would like to answer the question that the title of this paper poses:  Is atonement healing scriptural? Yes.  Although the answer to this question concurs with the atonenent healing advocates, the writer answers this question from a different perspective.  It is the purpose of this paper to present that perspective and to elucidate its qualifying statements.  There will be three primary areas of discussion:  (1) a validation of the miraculous gifts, (2) an examination of the passages used to support atonement healing and, (3) a re-evaluation of atonement healing re flecting the writer’s view.
    I.  The first topic of discussion will now be considered.  In that healing falls within the realm of the supernatural, it is felt that a study of the sign gifts as an active operation of the Spirit be validated.  The establishment of this premise is critical in that many in Christendom maintain that the miraculous aspect of God’s relationship to man has ceased.  Although some would not be so bold as to assert this belief, they, nevertheless, diminuate God’s power to
    the extent that they render him ineffectual.  The biblical text which deals with the sign gifts is found in 1 Cor. 12-14.  It is not the objective of this paper to treat the Corinthian text in its entirety, but merely consider a few verses of it.
    Some biblical scholars feel that the sign gifts ceased at the closing of the canon. The basis for this view is founded on their interpretation of 1 Cor. 13:8-10.
    “Charity never faileth; but whether there be prophecies, they shall fail; whether there be tongues, they shall cease; whether there be knowledge, it shall vanish away.  For we know in part, and we prophesy in part.  But when that which is perfect is come, then that which is in part shall be done away.”
    Although many scholars include all of the charismatic gifts in this cessation, others maintain that it pertained only to those specifically cited.  According to their reasoning, the sign gifts were necessary for the establishment of the infant (immature) church.  They argue that with the full revelation of the counsel of God’s will,that is, the completed New Testament, the provisional charismata (gifts) were no longer necessary.  Even a novice of early church history recognizes that the church plunged into apostasy toward the beginning of the 4 thcentury.  This is approximately the same period of time when the charismata were on the wane and the church entered its so called state of “maturity”.
    We will now further consider the passage of 1 Cor. 13:8-10.  In regard to the word “perfect” in verse 10, since it is neuter gender, they maintain that it cannot refer to Christ.  Consequently, the completed canon of scripture is said to be what the Apostle Paul was referring to.  Although “perfect” is neuter gender, to say that it refers to the completed canon is a forced interpretation, to say the least.  Thayer, in his famous Greek-English Lexicon, states that teleios (perfect) may have the following meanings:  “brought to its end, finished; wanting nothing necessary to completeness; perfect.” In reference to its usage in 1 Cor. 13:10, Thayer states that teleios refers to “the perfect state of all things, to be ushered in by the return of Christ from heaven.”  That this is the correct rendering is evident from the next two verses.
    “When I was a child, I spake as a child, I understood as a child. I thought as a child: but when I became a man, I put away childish things.
    For now we see through a glass, darkly; but then face to face:  now I know in part; but then shall I know even as also I am known.”
    In verse 11 Paul gives the analogy of maturation to show that the charismata will indeed cease, but that will only come when the church has reached its maturity.  When will this occur?  In Paul’s own words in 1 Cor. 15:23,24 “...afterward they that are Christ’s at his coming. Then cometh the end, when he shall have delivered up the kingdom to God, even the Father; when he shall have put down all rule and all authority and power.”
    With reference to verses 10 & 12, the Wycliffe Bible Commentary phrases it well:  “that which is perfect cannot be a reference to the completion of the canon of scripture; otherwise we now, living in the age of the completed canon, would see more clearly than Paul did.  Even the most self-satisfied and opinionated of theologians would hardly admit that.  The coming of that which is perfect can only be a reference to the Lord’s second coming.  That event will mark the end of the exercise of prophecy, tongues, and knowledge.”
    This is the concensus of most reputable biblical scholars.  Those that dogmaticly insist that verse 10 refers to the completed canon do so because of their biased and prejudiced theological views completely ignoring accepted grammatical hermeneutics.  Most theologians because of their professional integrity give the correct interpretation even in deference to their personal views.  Excerpts from a selection of various commentaries in regard to verse 10 will now be given. Matthew Henry’s Commentary.  “When the end is once attained, the means will of course be abolished.  There will be no need of tongues, and prophecy, and inspired knowledge, in a future life, because then the church will be in a state of perfection, complete both in knowledge and holiness...Such is the difference between earth and heaven.” Jamieson, Fausset, Brown Commentary.  “Shall be done away with, i.e., shall be dispensed with at the Lord’s coming, being superseded by their more perfect heavenly analogues.”
    Clark’s Commentary. “The state of eternal blessedness; that which is imperfect shall be done away; the imperfect as well as the probation-ing state shall cease forever.”
    Matthew Poole’s Commentary.  “But when we come to heaven, we shall be in such a state, as nothing shall or can be added to us; then our partial and imperfect knowledge shall be swallowed up in a knowledge perfect and complete.”
    The New Bible Commentary.  “Prophecy and tongues will not be necessary in the immediate presence of God...when the perfect comes:  not perfection in quality so much as totality; i.e., full knowledge about God.” The Expositor’s Greek Testament.  “But when there comes the perfect (full-grown, mature), the ‘in part* will be abolished; this teleiosis is brought about at the parousai—it ‘comes 1 with the Lord from heaven.”
    Although many scholars when exegeting verse 10 interpret it in reference to the time of Christ’s second advent will, in the very next verse, give a forced interpretation in order to maintain their established dogmas.  To illustrate this, an excerpt from the Wycliffe Bible Commentary will be given.
    “The coming of that which is perfect can only be a reference to the Lord’s second coming.  That event will mark the end of the exercise of prophecy, tongues, and knowledge.  How then can we speak of these gifts as temporary? The following verse will answer the question...With reference to these particular gifts, it may be likened to the growing up of a person from infancy to manhood.  The special and spectacular gifts were necessary in the early stages of the growth of the true church for purposes of authentication and edification when there was no New Testament to give light...today it is questionable that there exists anywhere the scriptural exercise of the three gifts referred to by Paul in this passage.” This is a classic example of theological “double-talk”.  With one breath he unequivocably states that the charismata were destined to continue until the second coming of Christ.  And in the very next breath states that they would last only until the New Testament was completely written.  The New Testament would then be the instrument used to give authentication and edification to the church.
    Another example of how scholarly theologians may sometimes allow good biblical hermeneutics to succ«mfcto their theological dogmas and denominational prejudices will be illustrated from A.T.Robertson’s Word Pictures in the New Testament.  He gives the following comment regarding 1 Cor. 13:8:  “All these special spiritual gifts will pass. It is amazing how little of human work lasts.” Because of his personal/ denominational biasness, he diminuates the Holy Spirit’s charismata (supernatural gifts) to the level of human work.  He also utilizes the
    ”last, therefore least” theory in reference to the gift of tongues. In commenting on 1 Cor. 12:10 he states:  “Paul placed this gift lowest of all.  It created wonder, but did little real good.”  In referring to the list of the charismata in 1 Cor. 12:28, Robertson succir&ly says, “...glSssSn(tongues), last again.”  He incorporates theological “double-talk” when commenting on tongues in 1 Cor. 13:1 whenUhe says, “mentioned first because really least;” Here, he changes direction in mid-stream.  It is a tortured logic that affirms as true mutually contradictory propositions.  Whether or not glSssOn-lalia (speaking in tongues) is indeed the least of the gifts should not be a matter of record.  One approaches the sphere of arrogance when it is stated that one of God’s gifts “created wonder, but did little real good.”  Ignorance of an experience does not authorize one to disclaim the reality or worth of that experience.
    The only point that is being stressed in the foregoing passage is that scholarly exegesis is sometimes sacrificed at the expense of preconceived denominational views.
    One wonders, then, why the supernatural gifts (healing included) gradually became a forgotten experience within the Christian church. A possible answer to this question may be gleaned from the Corinthian text presently being studied.  Since there was an obvious abuse and misuse of some of the charismata which God had given to the Body of Christ, there were segments of the Corinthian church which were trying to solve the problem by forbidding completely the exercise of some of these gifts during the worship service.  This can be seen from Paul’s words in 1 Cor. 14:39.
    “Wherefore, brethren, covet to prophesy, and forbid not to speak with tongues.”
    The tense of the verb form ‘forbid not 1 is known in the Greek as present imperative.  According to Dana and Mantey’s famous Greek Grammar, “a prohibition in the present imperative demands that action then in progress be stopped.” For example, the American Standard Version rendering of Matt. 7:1 is:  “judge not, that ye be not judged. 1 But this translation does not do justice to the real import of the idiom, which could be more accurately translated, “stop judging, lest you be judged.” Another illustration is Rev. 5:4,5:  “And I wept much, because no one was found worthy to open the book...and one of
    the elders saith unto me, weep not.” More precisely rendered, it means, “I was weeping...he said to me, stop weeping.”
    So, the Apostle Paul is actually saying “stop forbidding to speak with tongues.”  A similar problem was encountered by Paul in the church in Thessalonica.  There were certain Thessalonians who were also limiting and forbidding the exercise of certain of the sign gifts.  This was being done by conscientious Christians who were trying to combat gnostic influences who were abusing the spiritual gifts.  The gnostic’s expressions were frequently orgiastic.  Even its boasted “esoteric knowledge (gnSsis) was derived in part from ecstatic experiences” (The Abingdon Bible Commentary).  According to 1 Thess. 5:19,20, the Thessalonians were actively quenching the Spirit and were despising prophesyings.  The Pulpit Commentary gives the following comment concerning 1 Thess. 5:19,20:  “by the Spirit here is usually understood the miraculous gifts of the Spirit— speaking with tongues or prophesyings; and it is supposed that the apostle here forbids the exercise of these gifts being hindered or checked.”
    Although the motives of the Corinthian and Thessalonian Christ ians might have been noble, their actions were wrong.  They were, according to an old adage, “throwing the baby out with the bathwater.”
    We surmise that after the death of the Apostles the church manifested this same type of reactionary response in regard to a certain heresy known as Montanism which originated in the region of Phrygia.  Much of the following material concerning the heresy of Montanism will be taken from McClintock and Strong’s Cyclopedia of Biblical, Theological, and Ecclesiastical Literature.
    Montanus, the founder of a sect named after him Montanists, was a Phrygian by birth.  He was brought up in heathenism, but ap pears to have embraced Christianity (about 170 A.D.) with all the fanatical enthusiasm for which his countrymen were noted.  The frenzy, the paroxysms, the fierce belief in the supernatural that marked the old Phrygian priests of Cybele and Bacchus are repeated under less savage, but not less abnormal conditions, in the ecstasies of the Montanists.  His principal associates were two prophetesses, named Prisca, or Priscilla, and Maximilla.  These two women, after being indoctrinated by Montanus, abandoned their husbands in order to follow him.
    The Montanists proclaimed that the age of the Holy Ghost and the millennial reign had been established in the village of Papuza, in Western Phrygia, which they termed the New Jerusalem.  Those who followed the Holy Ghost, speaking through these new prophets, were held to be the only genuine Christians, and were to form the church. The Montanists believed that Christ, who came to fulfill the law and the prophets, and promised his Holy Spirit to his apostles to guide them into all truth, bequeathed to his church only an insufficient morality, and the Paraclete of Montanus was needed to supplement the new dispensation.  The Paraclete is undeniably identified with the promised Spirit of Truth, but was not ultimately given in its ful ness until the Spirit came on Montanus.
    Irenaeus, the bishop of Lyons (180-202 A.D.), was one of the great defenders of the Christian faith during the last part of the second century and beginning of the third century.  In the book, The Ante-Nicene Fathers, Irenaeus gives the following account con cerning Montanism in his treatise, “Irenaeus Against Heresies”.
    “Others, again (the Montanists), that they may set aside the gift of the Spirit which in the later times has been, by the good pleasure of the Father, poured out upon the human race, do not admit that aspect of the evangelical dispensation presented by John’s gospel, in which the Lord promised that He would send the Paraclete; but set aside at once both the gospel and the prophetic Spirit.  Wretched men indeed!  Who wish to be pseudo-prophets, forsooth, but who set at nought the gift of prohecy from the church... We must conclude, moreover, that these men (the Montanists) cannot admit the Apostle Paul either.  For, in his Epistle to the Corinthians, he speaks expressly of prophetical gifts, and recognizes men and women prophesying in the church.”
    It would seem that Irenaeus is saying in the above discourse that the Montanists deny the charismata.  But what he is really expressing, if his entire treatise against heresies is examined, is that the gifts that Montanus and his followers were exercising were false and do not have their origin from God.  The theory that this paper proposes to the reader is that the church, in order to combat
    this Phrygian heresy, began to quench the Holy Spirit’s operation in the worship services.  When there was a manifestation of one of the gifts of the Spirit, the church would automatically began to question within themselves whether this was truly from God or whether it was influenced by the Montanist heresy.  This proposition is given additional credence if one remembers that this is exactly what happened within the church at Corinth and the one in Thessa- lonica.
    Although all of God’s gifts are infallible, they operate through human vessels who are apt toward fallibility.  One must be spirit ually sensitive in any aspect of mediatorial ministry.
    In consideration of the preceding discussion, we propose that the reactions made by the church in response to counter-balance heresies is one of two primary factors that contributed to the cessation of the spiritual gifts.  Before we entertain the second factor, it is felt that an examination of some writings of the post-apostolic period is pertinent in order to establish the fact that the mirac ulous gifts did not cease with the completed .canon.
    Justin Martyr;  Dialogue with Trypho a Jew. (110-165 A.D.) “...knowing that daily some of you are becoming disciples in the name of Christ, and quitting the path of error; who are also receiv ing gifts, each as he is worthy, illumined through the name of this Christ.  For one receives the spirit of understanding, another of counsel, another of strength, another of healing, another of fore knowledge , another of teaching, and another of the fear of God.” “...for the prophetical giftsremain with us, even to the present time.  And hence you ought to understand that the gifts formerly among your nation have been transferred to us.”
