    “...Wherefore, also, those who are in truth His disciples, receiv ing grace from Him, do in His name perform miracles, so as to promote the welfare of other men, according to the gift which each one has received from Him.  For some do certainly and truly drive out devils, so that those who have thus been cleansed from evil spirits frequently believe in Christ.  Others have foreknowledge of
    things to come:  they see visions, and utter prophetic expressions. Others still, heal the sick by laying their hands upon them, and they are made whole.  Yea, moreover, as I have said, the dead even have been raised up, and remained among us for many years.  And what shall I more say?  It is not possible to name the number of the gifts which the church scattered throughout the whole world, has received from God, in the name of Jesus Christ, who was crucified under Pontius Pilate, and which she exerts day by day for the benefit of the Gentiles.”
    “...In like manner we do also hear many brethren in the church, who possess prophetic gifts, and who through the Spirit speak all kinds of languages, and bring to light for the general benefit the hidden things of men, and declare the mysteries of God.” i      As is evident from writings of the early church fathers, the charismata continued to be operative in the early church.  But a closer examination of early church history reveals that they became, for all practical purposes, extinct toward the beginning of the 4 th century.  This brings us to the second proposed factor that contributed to their cessation.
    Under the rule of the Roman Empire, the church went through ten general persecutions beginning with Nero in 64 A.D. and ending with the Emperor Diocletian from 303 A.D. to 313 A.D.  History re cords that this last persecution was the most severe and cruel of any previous reign of terror.  In fact, Diocletian had a. coin struck to commemorate the terminus of Christianity.
    After the death of Diocletian, Constantine became the next Emperor of the Roman Empire.  He allegedly had a conversion exper ience in 312 A.D.  All persecutions ceased with his edict of 313 A.D, In fact, Christianity was then instituted as the new state religion. Some may deem this as a victory for the Christian faith, but in reality, it promoted its apostasy.  Christianity was now in i4fe .vogue.  Pagans by the multiplied thousands went under the name of “Christian”.  McClintock and Strong’s Cyclopedia of Biblical, Theological, and Ecclesiastical Literature has this to say concerning this era:
    “The simplicity of the Gospel was corrupted; pompous rites and ceremonies were introduced; worldly honors were conferred on the teachers of Christianity, and the kingdom
    of Christ in a great measure converted into a kingdom of this world.”
    So, in conclusion, it is seen that the two primary factors which were instrumental in the decline and cessation of the charismata were (1) the Church’s reaction to heresy, and, (2) a world-wide apostasy within the Christian faith.
    Much time has been used to establish the premise that the spirit ual gifts were destined to continue throughout the church age.  This was a necessary foundation since the topic of this paper involves one of the supernatural aspects of God’s graces.
