    REASON II.  Again, all Christians should expect God to heal their bodies today, because Christ died to atone for our sicknesses as well as for our sins.
    The passage used to support atonement healing is found in Isa. 53:4,5.
    “Surely he hath borne our griefs, and carried our sorrows: yet we did esteem him stricken, smitten of God, and af flicted.
    But he was wounded for our transgressions, he was bruised for iniquities: the chastisement of our peace was upon him; and with his stripes we are healed.”
    If one were to read the Isaiah passage from the King James version, the idea of suffering for the expiation of our sins would seem to be all that was involved.  For instance, within verse 5 there are four phrases that are employed to describe the same action.
    This is known as synonymous parallelism.  Other examples of this may be seen in Gen.2:4; Isa.43:7; and Isa.45:7.  The parallels are wounded-transgressions, bruised-iniquities, chastisement-peace, and stripes-healed.  In the context, the atoning of sins or spiritual healing would appear to be all that is under consideration.
    We will now do a word study to determine whether or not this is in fact the situation.  The Hebrew word for griefs is choli. According to Young ’s Analytical Concordance, choli denotes sickness, weakness and pain.  It is this word which elsewhere in the Old Testament is translated sickness (Deut. 7:15; 28:61; 2Chron.21:15; Isa.38:9).  The Hebrew word translated sorrows is makob.  In Strong’s Exhaustive Concordance, it is given the definition of pain or sorrows, and is translated pain in Job 33:19 and Jer.51:8.  In reference to the word healing (rapha) in verse 5, the Theological Wordbook of the Old Testament says that it means to heal or make healthful. It may refer to the restoration or healing of either the soul or the body.
    Keil and Delitzsch in their erudite Commentary on the Old Test amentgives the following comment on the verses under consideration: “In 4a it is not really sin that is spoken of, but the evil which is consequent upon human sin, although not al ways the direct consequence of the sins of individuals. But in the fact that He was concerned to relieve this evil in all its forms, whenever it came in His way in the exercise of His calling, the relief implied as a consequence in verse 4a was brought distinctly into view...it is evident that both of these are to be understood in the sense of an expiatory bearing, and not merely of taking away...But in the case before us, where it is not the sins, but our diseases and our pains that are the object, this mediatorial sense remains essentially the same.  The meaning is not merely that the Servant of God entered into the fellowship of our sufferings, but that He took upon Himself the sufferings which we had to bear and deserved to bear, and therfore not only took them away, but bore them in His own person, that He might deliver us from them...It was our peace, or, what is more in accordance
    with the full idea of the word, our general well-being
    which these sufferings arrived at and secured...The stripes and weals that were inflicted upon Him have made us sound and well.”
    The Isaiah passage gives a graphic account of the Suffering Messiah and his purpose of reconciliation accomplished at his first advent.  Alexander McLaren, in his Commentary, has this to say a- bout the Isaiah passage:
    “It is to be kept in view, that the griefs, which the Ser vant (Christ) is here described as bearing, are literally sicknesses, and that similarly, the sorrows may be diseases. Matthew in his quotation of this verse (Matt.8:16,17) takes the words to refer to bodily ailments—and that interpre tation is part of the whole truth, for Hebrew thought drew no such sharp line of distinction between diseases of the body and those of the soul, as we are accustomed to draw. All sicknesses was taken to be the consequence of sin.” Dr. McCrossan states that the opponents of atonement healing argue that ‘the prophecy of Isaiah was fulfilled in the day when our Lord healed the great multitude.  It was fulfilled about three years before the Lord died on the cross.  The prophecy of Isaiah was fulfilled in his divine ministry of healing during his first advent and is not applicable for us today 1 .
    In refuting this argument, Dr. McCrossan examines Matt.12:17-21. I will now quote verbatim his rebuttal of this line of reasoning.
    “...Here, then, is a great prediction from Isaiah that in the future, (1) the Gentile nations would yet hear the Gospel and find hope in Christ, and (2) that Christ would yet hurl forth judgment unto victory (referring to His coming in vengeance to destroy all His enemies); and yet—wonderful to narrate—Matthew here declares that this prophecy of Isaiah was then fulfilled, even before the Gentiles had yet heard the Gospel; and he uses the very same word to express this fulfillment that he uses in Matthew 8:17; viz., plerothe, the 1 st aorist passive, subjunctive, 3 rd person singular of the verb pleroo, I fulfill.
    Matthew asserts in Matthew 12:17 that Christ did what He did on this occasion, ‘That it might be fulfilled (plerothe) ,
    which was spoken by Esaias the prophet,’ and he here uses the very same word for ‘fulfill’ (plerothe) that he uses in Matthew 8:17 regarding the fulfillment of Isaiah 53:4. Why did Matthew declare in Matthew 12:17 that this great prophecy of Isaiah 42:1-4 was fulfilled at this time—when it would not be fulfilled ‘until Jesus sets up His eternal kingdom?  Because, from God’s standpoint, it was really fulfilled just as soon as Christ was here on earth, and began His saving ministry.”
