    From this passage, we find seven points worthy of consideration.
    (1) Thou sealest up the sum.  The act of sealing has reference to the signet ring. After a letter, document, or container had been closed, then some clay/wax was placed over the seal and then imprinted with the signet. This secured its privacy.  So, the “sealing up” was the last act done.  The “sum” has reference to the sum total of all the various strengths and beauties of the angelic host in totality.  Whereas some angels might have had few or maybe many strengths/glories, Lucifer possessed all the qualities which were given by God to this newly created host.
    (2) Full of wisdom.  Lucifer had full wisdom and knowledge of God’s total creation.  Everything that God created or would create in the future, Lucifer was given the knowledge of all the mysteries and magnificent wonders which were contained in all of God’s creation. Not only did he possess full wisdom and knowledge of God’s material and spiritual creative acts, he also, more than any other created being, was fully cognizant of the nature of God. Because of this knowledge, he was held accountable for his rebellious act and was not given a “second chance”.  “To whom much is given, much is required”.
    (3) Perfect in beauty.  It would be pure conjecture to begin to des cribe exactly in what ways angels are assigned variations in their beauty. It seems totally out of context for them to have some aberration such as a “spiritual wart”.  However, we do know that there are gradations in rank and power in the angelic realm.
    (4) The workmanship of thy tabrets and of thy pipes was prepared in thee.  Lucifer was created with the ability to produce music.  No doubt from his being came forth the most melodious sounds ever produced from God’s creation, and these were all sounds of praise to God.
    (5) Anointed cherub that covereth.  Here we see that Lucifer was ordained (anointed) for a specific purpose.  His position was that of authority over all the angels. The word for “covereth” denotes protect-tion and hence overseer or ruler of the angelic host.  Like the first phrase discussed, “thou sealest up the sum”, I believe this phrase also carries with it the connotation that Lucifer was the last angel created.
    (2)
