    With this position in mind, one can readily see how Satan was working behind the scenes to further his goals.  Of course, we know the “rest of the story”, as Paul Harvey characteristically phrases it.  God judged this wicked antediluvian world by destroying it with a global flood.
    This did not dampen Satan’s attempt at world domination, however. In Genesis 10 & 11, we find Satan making still another attempt at controlling the destiny of man.
    “And Cush begat Nimrod; he began to be a mighty one in the earth.
    He was a mighty hunter before the LORD: wherefore it is said, Even as Nimrod the mighty hunter before the LORD. And the beginning of his kingdom was Babel, and Erech, and Accad, and Calneh, in the land of Shinar.” (Gen.10:8-10).
    From these few obscure verses, Rev. Alexander Hislop in his book, The Two Babylons, traces the ancient Babylonian, Roman, and Grecian pantheons as originating from the worship of Nimrod.  His work is a comprehensive study of pagan religions from an etymological, historical, and cultural perspective.  It is a monumental work which is fully documented.
    Adam Clarke gives some very enlightening comments concerning Nimrod.
    “His name Nimrod comes from marad, he rebelled; and the Targum, on 1 Chron.l:10, says: ‘Nimrod began to be a mighty man in sin, a murderer of innocent men, and a rebel before the Lord’.  The Jerusalem Targum says:  ‘He was mighty in hunting (or in prey) and in sin before God, for he was a hunter of the children of men in their languages; and he said unto them, Depart from the religion of Shem, and cleave to the institutes
    (15)
    of Nimrod’.  The Syriac calls him a warlike giant.  The word tsayid, which we render hunter, signifies prey; and is applied in the Scriptures to the hunting of men by persecution, oppression, and tyranny.  Hence it is likely that Nimrod, having acquired power, used it in tyranny and oppression; and by rapine and violence founded that domination which was the first distinguished by the name of a kingdom on the face of the earth.”
    So, from these accounts, we can see how Satan manipulated man in a great apostasy against God. Again, God supernaturally intervenes with the confusion of languages.  The brevity of this paper will not permit us to delineate every circumstance in which Satan manuevered behind the scenes to destroy the chosen race which would one day bring forth the “Deliverer”.
    The next segment of this unfolding drama brings us to the birth of Christ.  Satan’s role in this scene is illustrated in the twelfth chapter of Revelation.
    “And there appeared a great wonder in heaven; a woman clothed with the sun, and the moon under her feet, and upon her head a crown of twelve stars:
    And she being with child cried, travailing in birth, and pained to be delivered.
    And there appeared another wonder in heaven; and behold a great red dragon, having seven heads and ten horns, and seven crowns upon his heads.
    And his tail drew the third part of the stars of heaven, and did cast them to the earth: and the dragon stood before the woman which was ready to be delivered, for to devour her child as soon as it was born.
    And she brought forth a man child, who was to rule all nations with a rod of iron: and her child was caught up unto God, and to his throne.” (Rev.12:1-5).
    Satan knew that this was his “last chance”.  He knew that if Jesus succeeded in his mission to earth, then all hope for him (Satan) to have his sentence and judgment reprieved would be hopelessly lost.  Failing in his efforts to destroy Christ in his infanthood, he later tries to persuade Jesus in the “desert temptation” to worship him, again without any success. Satan was utterly and ultimately defeated at the death of Christ and his resultant resurrection.
    In this paper, we have presented the thesis that Satan’s attacks on man are based on an ulterior motive that if mankind would totally aposta-size against God, then God would (because of his great love for man—Jn.3:lo) somehow absolve man of his sin.  Satan thus reasoned that this would be evidence of an inequity in the justice of God and that God would be obligated to absolve him also of his infamous sin of rebellion.  With this in
