    mind, one may wonder what continues to motivate Satan in his assaults against man.  The only logical answer accounting for his relentless fury aimed at mankind must be attributed to his unadulterated hatred against this most treasured of God’s creation. This hatred is most probably due to his jealousy of man’s potentially exalted position which he himself lusted after eons before.  The very glory that he desired to share with God will one day be shared with this newest creation of God.  Cognizant of his own doomed destiny, he now tirelessly tries to infect man with that rebellious spirit which resulted in his own downfall.
    At this point, the reader probably thinks’ that this must be the end of this ignoble saga between Satan and man.  It would be except for one other scenario that is worthy of consideration.
    We have previously made the presumption that Satan’s master plan against man was entirely his own fabrication.  But the Bible allows for another possible proposition.  The first hint we find in the Bible concerning this inconceivable supposition is found in Job 1:8.
    “And the LORD said unto Satan, Hast thou considered my servant Job, that there is none like him in the earth, a perfect and an upright man, one that feareth God, and escheweth evil?”
    Here, we notice that God actually challenges Satan to try and dissuade Job from serving God.  Could it be possible that it was God who initiated this bold proposal to Satan that “if man utterly failed in serving God then indeed Satan would be given a reprieve?” Since this may be a revolutionary new concept, your first reply might well be—Preposterous! But before you completely dismiss the idea, consider for a moment the basis for such an argument.
    Let ’s look again at the text in Job.
    “Now there was a day when the sons of God came to present themselves before the LORD, and Satan came also among them. And the LORD said unto Satan, Whence comest thou? Then Satan answered the LORD, and said, From going to and fro in the earth, and from walking up and down in it.
    And the LORD said unto Satan, Hast thou considered my servant Job, that there is none like him in the earth, a perfect and an upright man, one that feareth God, and escheweth evil? Then Satan answered the LORD, and said, Doth Job fear God for nought?
    Hast not thou made an hedge about him, and about his house, and about all that he hath on every side? thou hast blessed the work of his hands, and his substance is increased in the land. But put forth thine hand now, and touch all that he hath, and he will curse thee to thy face.”
